e Haunted Lake, Midnight Adventure, Supper is Served, Exchange is No Robbery)\n*''The Invisible Companion and Other Stories'' (1946) (February the Seventh, In Reverse, The Invisible Companion, The Room That Got Lost, Supper Is Served)\n*''Midnight Adventure and Other Stories'' (1946) (Midnight Adventure, The Vase and the Candlestick, Waiting for the Police, It Happened in the Fog, Exchange is No Robbery)\n\n===Other short stories===\n*''The Tale of A Hat (A Romance of the Thames)'' [[Pearson's Magazine]] issue 172 April 1910\n\n===Plays===\n*''[[Number 17 (play)|Number 17]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[After Dark (Farjeon play)|After Dark]]'' (1926)\n*''Enchantment'' (1927)\n*''Philomel'' (1932)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Other sources ==\n\n*Bordman, Gerald Martin. ''American Theatre: A Chronicle of Comedy and Drama, 1914\u20131930''. Oxford University Press, 1995.\n*Krueger, Christine L. ''Encyclopedia of British Writers, 19th Century''. Infobase Publishing, 2003.\n\n==External links==\n* {{FadedPage|id=Farjeon, J. Jefferson|name=Joseph Jefferson Farjeon|author=yes}}\n* {{LCAuth|no97055650|J. Jefferson Farjeon|47|ue}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farjeon, Joseph Jefferson}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:English crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:English screenwriters]]\n[[Category:English male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Farjeon family|Joseph]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily:Unlikely redlink;", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Jefferson_Farjeon"}
{"title_page": "32nd United States Congress", "text_new": "{{Infobox United States Congress\n| number                   = 32nd\n| image                    = Capitol1846.jpg\n| imagename                = [[United States Capitol]]\n| imagedate                = 1846\n| start                    = March 4, 1851\n| end                      = March 4, 1853\n| vp                       = Vacant\n| pro tem                  = [[William R. King]] (D)<br>[[David Rice Atchison|David R. Atchison]] (D)\n| speaker                  = [[Linn Boyd]] (D)\n| senators                 = 62\n| reps                     = 233\n| delegates                = 4\n| s-majority               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| h-majority               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| sessionnumber1           = Special\n| sessionstart1            = March 4, 1851\n| sessionend1              = March 13, 1851\n| sessionnumber2           = 1st\n| sessionstart2            = December 1, 1851\n| sessionend2              = August 31, 1852\n| sessionnumber3           = 2nd\n| sessionstart3            = December 6, 1852\n| sessionend3              = March 4, 1853\n| previous                 = 31st\n| next                     = 33rd\n}}\nThe '''Thirty-second United States Congress''' was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the [[United States Senate]] and the [[United States House of Representatives]]. It met in [[Washington, D.C.]] from March 4, 1851, to March 4, 1853, during the last two years of [[Millard Fillmore]]'s [[Presidency of Millard Fillmore|presidency]]. The apportionment of seats in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] was based on the [[1840 United States Census|Sixth Census of the United States in 1840]]. Both chambers had a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] majority.\n\nIt was one of the least productive Congresses, forwarding only 74 bills that were signed by the [[POTUS|president]].<ref>{{cite book |first=David M. |last=Faris |title=It's Time to Fight Dirty: How Democrats Can Build a Lasting Majority in American Politics  |url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=MPcsDwAAQBAJ |year=2018 |pages=123 |publisher=[[Melville House Publishing]] |isbn=978-1612196954}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Major events ==\n\n[[File:UncleTomsCabinCover.jpg|thumb|[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]] was published in 1852]]\n{{Main|1851 in the United States|1852 in the United States|1853 in the United States}}\n* March 20, 1852: [[Uncle Tom's Cabin]] published.\n* July 1, 1852: [[Henry Clay]] was the first to [[lie in state]] in the [[United States Capitol rotunda]].\n* November 2, 1852: [[1852 United States presidential election]]: Democrat [[Franklin Pierce]] defeated Whig [[Winfield Scott]].\n\n== Major legislation ==\n\n{{main|List of United States federal legislation, 1789\u20131901|l1=Major legislation: 32nd United States Congress}}\n* March 2, 1853: An act providing for administering the oath of office to William R. King, Vice President elect of the United States of America. Sess. 2, Ch. 93, {{USStat|10|180}}\n\n== Territories organized ==\n\n* March 2, 1853: [[Washington Territory]] was formed from [[Oregon Territory]].\n\n== Party summary ==\n\n=== Senate ===\n{{US Congress party summary\n| congress           = 32\n\n| party1             = Democratic\n| abb1               = D\n| seats1_last        = 36\n| seats1_begin       = 34\n| seats1_end         = 35\n| seats1_next        = 36\n\n| party2             = Free Soil\n| abb2               = FS\n| seats2_last        = 2\n| seats2_begin       = 2\n| seats2_end         = 3\n| seats2_next        = 3\n\n| party3             = Whig\n| abb3               = W\n| seats3_last        = 24\n| seats3_begin       = 21\n| seats3_end         = 23\n| seats3_next        = 22\n\n| seats_vacant_last  = 0\n| seats_vacant_begin = 5\n| seats_vacant_end   = 1\n| seats_vacant_next  = 2\n\n}}\n\n=== House of Representatives===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- valign=bottom\n! rowspan=3 | &nbsp;\n! colspan=8 | Party <div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Shading indicates majority caucus)</div>\n! rowspan=3 | Total\n! rowspan=3 | Vacant\n\n|- style=\"height:5px\"\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | \n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | \n| {{party shading/Free Soil}} | \n| {{party shading/States Rights}} | \n| {{party shading/Unionist}} | \n| {{party shading/Whig}} | \n| {{party shading/Whig}} | \n| {{party shading/Other}} | \n\n|- valign=bottom\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]<br/>(D)\n! Independent<br/>Democratic<br/>(ID)\n! [[Free Soil Party|Free<br/>Soil]]<br/>(FS)\n! States'<br/>Rights<br/>(SR)\n! [[Unionist Party (United States)|Unionist]]<br/>(U)\n! [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]]<br/>(W)\n! Independent<br/>Whig<br/>(IW)\n! Other\n\n|-\n! style=\"white-space:nowrap; font-size:80%;\"| End of [[31st United States Congress|previous Congress]]\n| <!--D-->{{party shading/Democratic}} | 113\n| <!--ID-->0\n| <!--FS-->9\n| <!--SR-->0\n| <!--U-->0\n| <!--W-->107\n| <!--IW-->0\n| <!--O-->2\n! 231\n| 2\n\n|-\n| colspan=99 | \n\n|-\n! Begin\n| <!--D-->{{party shading/Democratic}} | 127\n| <!--ID-->rowspan=2 | 3\n| <!--FS-->rowspan=2 | 4\n| <!--SR-->rowspan=2 | 3\n| <!--U-->rowspan=2 | 10\n| <!--W-->85\n| <!--IW-->rowspan=2 | 1\n| <!--O-->rowspan=2 | 0\n! 233\n| 0\n\n|-\n! End\n| <!--D-->{{party shading/Democratic}} | 125\n| <!--W-->86\n! 232\n| 1\n\n|-\n! Final voting share\n! <!--D-->{{party shading/Democratic}} | 54.7%<!--125/232-->\n! <!--ID-->1.3%<!--3/232-->\n! <!--FS-->1.3%<!--4/232-->\n! <!--SR-->1.3%<!--3/232-->\n! <!--U-->4.3%<!--10/232-->\n! <!--W-->36.8%<!--86/232-->\n! <!--IW-->0.4%<!--1/232-->\n! <!--O-->0.0%<!--0/232-->\n| colspan=2 | \n\n|-\n| colspan=99 | \n\n|-\n! style=\"white-space:nowrap; font-size:80%;\"| Beginning of [[33rd United States Congress|next Congress]]\n| <!--D-->{{party shading/Democratic}} | 158\n| <!--ID-->1\n| <!--FS-->3\n| <!--SR-->0\n| <!--U-->0\n| <!--W-->71\n| <!--IW-->0\n| <!--O-->1\n! 234\n| 0\n\n|}\n\n== Leadership ==\n\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n| header = <big>'''Senate Presidents pro Tempore'''</big>\n\n| image1 = William Rufus DeVane King 1839 portrait.jpg\n| width1 = 175\n| alt1 = William R. D. King\n| caption1 = [[William R. King]] (D)<br/>(until December 20, 1852)\n\n| image2 = David Rice Atchison.jpg\n| width2 = 183\n| alt2 = David R. Atchison\n| caption2 = [[David R. Atchison]] (D)<br/>(from December 20, 1852)\n}}\n\n=== Senate ===\n* [[President of the United States Senate|President]]: Vacant (since the ascension of [[Millard Fillmore]] to [[U.S. President]] on July 9, 1850)\n* [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|President pro tempore]]: [[William R. King]] (D), until December 20, 1852\n** [[David Rice Atchison|David R. Atchison]] (D), from December 20, 1852\n\n=== House of Representatives ===\n* [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]]: [[Linn Boyd]] (D)\n\n== Members ==\n\nThis list is arranged by chamber, then by state. Senators are listed by class and Representatives by district.\n\n=== Senate===\nSenators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress. Preceding the names in the list below are [[Classes of United States Senators|Senate class numbers]], which indicate the cycle of their election. In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, facing re-election in 1856; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, facing re-election in 1852; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, facing re-election in 1854.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Alabama|Alabama]] ====\n* 2. [[Jeremiah Clemens]] (D)\n* 3. [[William R. King]] (D), until December 20, 1852\n** [[Benjamin Fitzpatrick]] (D), from January 14, 1853\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Arkansas|Arkansas]] ====\n* 2. [[William King Sebastian|William K. Sebastian]] (D)\n* 3. [[Solon Borland]] (D)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from California|California]] ====\n* 1. [[John B. Weller]] (D), from January 30, 1852\n* 3. [[William M. Gwin]] (D)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Connecticut|Connecticut]] ====\n* 1. [[Isaac Toucey]] (D), from May 12, 1852\n* 3. [[Truman Smith]] (W)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Delaware|Delaware]] ====\n* 1. [[James A. Bayard, Jr.]] (D)\n* 2. [[Presley Spruance]] (W)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Florida|Florida]] ====\n* 1. [[Stephen Mallory]] (D)\n* 3. [[Jackson Morton]] (W)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Georgia|Georgia]] ====\n* 2. [[John M. Berrien]] (W), until May 28, 1852\n** [[Robert M. Charlton]] (D), from May 31, 1852\n* 3. [[William Crosby Dawson|William C. Dawson]] (W)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Illinois|Illinois]] ====\n* 2. [[Stephen A. Douglas]] (D)\n* 3. [[James Shields (politician, born 1810)|James Shields]] (D)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Indiana|Indiana]] ====\n* 1. [[Jesse D. Bright]] (D)\n* 3. [[James Whitcomb]] (D), until October 4, 1852\n** [[Charles W. Cathcart]] (D), from December 6, 1852, until January 18, 1853\n** [[John Pettit]] (D), from January 18, 1853\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Iowa|Iowa]] ====\n* 2. [[George W. Jones]] (D)\n* 3. [[Augustus C. Dodge]] (D)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Kentucky|Kentucky]] ====\n* 2. [[Joseph R. Underwood]] (W)\n* 3. [[Henry Clay]] (W), until June 29, 1852\n** [[David Meriwether (senator)|David Meriwether]] (D), from July 6, 1852, until August 31, 1852\n** [[Archibald Dixon]] (W), from September 1, 1852\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Louisiana|Louisiana]] ====\n* 2. [[Solomon W. Downs]] (D)\n* 3. [[Pierre Soul\u00e9]] (D)\n\n==== [[List of United States Senators from Maine|Maine]] ====\n* 1. [[