onias]]\n[[Category:Current events]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in China]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in China]]\n[[Category:History of Wuhan]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in China]]\n[[Category:Occupational safety and health]]\n[[Category:Pandemics]]\n[[Category:Pandemics with high degree of misinformation]]\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern]]\n", "name_user": "Alpha Centauri 5932", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChina", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "La Masia", "text_new": "{{For|a type of rural construction common to the Catalan Countries|Masia}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                 = La Masia de Can Planes\n| alternate_names      = La Masia\n| image                = La Masia (Can Planas) (Barcelona) - 1.jpg\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = Main fa\u00e7ade of La Masia\n| map_type             =Spain\n| map_alt              =\n| map_caption          = Location within [[Spain]]\n| owner                = [[FC Barcelona]]\n| location_city        = [[Barcelona]]\n| location_country     =  Spain\n| coordinates          = {{coord|41.3831|N|2.1231|E|region:ES-CT_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date           =\n| completion_date      = 1702\n| inauguration_date    =\n| renovation_date      = 1966\n}}\n\n'''La Masia de Can Planes''', usually shortened to '''La Masia''' ({{IPA-ca|l\u0259 m\u0259\u02c8zi.\u0259}}; {{lang-en|\"The Farmhouse\"}}),<ref name=\"scholastic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.scholastic.com/browse/article.jsp?id=3754451 |title=School of Soccer Champions |publisher=Scholastic |author=Price, Sean |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> is a term used for [[FC Barcelona]]'s [[youth academy]]. The academy includes more than 300 young players. It has been a significant factor in Barcelona's European success, and produced some world class players in the early 2000s.\n\nIn 2010, La Masia became the first youth academy to have trained all three finalists for the [[FIFA Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]] in a single year - [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], [[Lionel Messi]] and [[Xavi]].<ref name=\"3players\">totalbarca.com, [http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/its-an-all-barca-affair-at-fifa-ballon-dor/ It\u2019s an all Bar\u00e7a affair at FIFA Ballon d\u2019Or] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210060409/http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/its-an-all-barca-affair-at-fifa-ballon-dor/ |date=December 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nLa Masia is also the name of FC Barcelona's football training facilities, originally located near the [[Camp Nou]] in the [[District of Les Corts|Les Corts]] district of [[Barcelona]]. The original building itself was an ancient country residence (In [[Catalan language|Catalan]]: [[masia]]) built in 1702, and once Camp Nou was inaugurated in 1957, the building was remodelled and extended for use as the club's social headquarters. With the gradual expansion of the club, the building became too small for headquarters, and on 20 October 1979, La Masia was converted into a dormitory for young players from outside Barcelona. On 30 June 2011, the Masia building ceased housing the academy players. In a simple ceremony, the doors were closed and the [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]] took over the function of the residential center for the players.\n\n==History==\n{{Johan Cruyff series}}\n[[File:Johan Cruijff 2013 Catalonia.jpg|thumb|right|[[Johan Cruyff]] in 2013. In [[Xavi]]'s words (2016), \"Cruyff established a very clear philosophy at Barcelona, he gave birth to that philosophy, he created Bar\u00e7a's DNA.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.as.com/en/2016/05/02/football/1462198310_725250.html |author=Jim\u00e9nez, Mayca |title=Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez critical of Atl\u00e9tico Madrid's playing style |publisher=AS.com (Diario AS) |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=22 August 2016 }}</ref> La Masia's coaching system is often considered as the foremost bastion of Cruyffian (Bar\u00e7ajax) school of football.]]\nLa Masia de Can Planes was an old Catalan farmhouse, built in 1702. In 1979, it was first used by the club to house its young footballers who originated from outside Barcelona.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite web|last=Rogers |first=Iain |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE59L02D20091022 |title=Barca talent farm marks 30 years of success |publisher=Reuters |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> The idea for the youth academy was proposed to N\u00fa\u00f1ez by Jaume Amat<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD03/PUB/2009/10/21/EMD20091021022MDP.pdf|title=La Mas\u00eda naci\u00f3 en un minuto |publisher=Mundo Deportivo |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>, and Oriol Tort was put in charge of the facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w2.bcn.cat/bcnmetropolis/en/calaixera/biografies/oriol-tort-lanima-de-la-masia-del-barca/|title=Oriol Tort, the soul of Bar\u00e7a\u2019s Masia|last=Genis Sinca|work=Barcelona Metropolis|publisher=Ayuntament de Barcelona|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, it was announced that Barcelona would be moving all its football training activities to La [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/inside-ciutat-esportiva-joan-gamper/|title=Inside : Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper|date=29 September 2011|publisher=Inside Spanish Football|accessdate=11 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130629125931/http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/inside-ciutat-esportiva-joan-gamper/|archivedate=29 June 2013}} </ref>\n\nLa Masia received more publicity after Barcelona B's success with homegrown players; Rory Smith reported in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that La Masia \"has replaced the fabled [[Ajax Academy]] as football's foremost production line\".<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Rory |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup-2010/teams/spain/7895208/World-Cup-2010-Spains-battle-won-on-the-playing-fields-of-Barcelona.html |title=World Cup 2010: Spain's battle won on the playing fields of Barcelona |publisher=Telegraph |date=17 July 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> The recent fame and success of La Masia as a talent school was ascribed by Ian Hawkey of ''[[The Times]]'' to the class of 1987, which featured prominent members such as [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]], [[Lionel Messi]], [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]] and [[Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)|Pedro]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/european_football/article7078610.ece |author=Hawkey, Ian |publisher=The Times |date=28 March 2010 |title=Friends reunited: Cesc Fabregas and the class of 1987 |accessdate=30 July 2010}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In 2000, [[Louis van Gaal]], coach of Barcelona's first team, was widely ridiculed by the city sports media for his dream to win the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] with 11&nbsp;home-grown players. The first team won the trophy in 2009 with eight home-grown players.<ref name=\"sport1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sport.es/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=44&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=724176&idseccio_PK=803 |title=La Masia, como un laboratorio |publisher=SPORT.es |accessdate=19 August 2010 |language=Spanish |author=Perarnau, Mart\u00ed |date=18 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=February 2013}}{{cbignore}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979 to 2009, 440&nbsp;youngsters have left their homes and families to stay at the academy. About half of them were from [[Catalonia]], and the rest came from other regions of the [[Kingdom of Spain]] and beyond, including 15 from [[Cameroon]], 7 from [[Brazil]], 5 from [[Senegal]] and 3 from [[Argentina]]. Of those 440, 40&nbsp;made it into Barcelona's first team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKLO72065620090525 |first=Iain |last=Rogers |title=INTERVIEW-Soccer-La Masia a fertile breeding ground for Barca |publisher=Reuters |date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nLa Masia houses about 60 players: 10 in the farmhouse, and the rest in rooms of the adjacent stadium; the rest of the youth players must provide for their own accommodation.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/><ref name=\"dailymail1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1261064/Lionel-Messi-Cesc-Fabregas-Gerard-Pique--forged-Barcelonas-hothouse-champions.html |title=Lionel Messi, Cesc Fabregas, Gerard Pique... all forged in Barcelona's hothouse of champions |author=Kay, Alex |publisher=Daily Mail |date=27 March 2010 |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref>\nThe academy is one of the most expensive in Europe, operating at a cost of \u00a35&nbsp;million a year. The main cost is the dormitory, La Masia itself.<ref name=\"dailymail1\"/> The minimum age for the youth program is six years; each year, more than 1,000&nbsp;boys from the ages of six to eight try out for admittance. The best 200 are selected.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 39</ref> The club also actively seeks for prospective students; it employs a system in which 15&nbsp;scouts are deployed in Catalonia, 15 in the rest of Spain and 10 scattered throughout the world. To alleviate the expenses of this scouting, the club has an agreement with 15 local clubs for them to train players who are not ready for entry into the youth academy. In return, FC Barcelona gives money, coaching and technical advice to these clubs for their services.<ref name=mcshane53>McShane, Kevin. p. 53</ref> While expanding its operations abroad, the club established five schools in Mexico and one in Egypt; successful applicants to these schools become full-time students, receiving academic education and football training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/futbol/futbol_base/FCBEscola/FCBEscola.html |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091003160049/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/futbol/futbol_base/FCBEscola/FCBEscola.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 October 2009 |title=FCBEscola |publisher=FC Barcelona |accessdate=14 August 2010 }}</ref>\n[[File:S. Busquets (2009-05).jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Sergio Busquets]], a graduate of La Masia, has been a part of the Barcelona first team since 2008.]]\n\nWhen Guardiola re-organised the reserve side, he set up a three-staged program to formalise the advancement from Juvenil to Barcelona B and finally to the first team. The first stage of a youth player's career involves a rotation scheme with Barcelona B. The second stage involves making the player aware of his importance to the team and the expectation that the player will improve cohesion and performance within the reserve side. In the last stage, he is designated a \"key\" player of the B team and might be called to the first team. One of the players in the third phase is made captain, regardless of the experience of older players.<ref name=\"sport1\"/>\n\nThe teams at Barcelona play from August to May; mild weather at La Masia allows players to train outdoors throughout the year. The youth teams train after school; Barcelona B plays  as a professional team, training in the morning and evening.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 74-79</ref> All of the trainers at FC Barcelona are former professional footballers.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 105</ref>\n\n[[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]], the club's main youth team, and the 12 other youth teams contained 24 coaches and more than 300 players. There are 56 other employees, including doctors, psychologists, nutritionists, cooks and physiologists.<ref name=\"dailymail1\"/> In the 2009\u201310 season, the B team qualified for the Segunda Divisi\u00f3n again. Barcelona B play in a 4\u20133\u20133 [[Formation (association football)|formation]], which is the same formation employed by the first team.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 77</ref>\n\n==Philosophy==\n[[File:Masia-AmorFerrerMussonsGuardiola.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Guillermo Amor]], [[Albert Ferrer]], Josep Mussons (Bar\u00e7a Vice-president) and [[Pep Guardiola]]. This photo was displayed for many years at the entrance of La Masia dining room. Their signature, in [[Catalan language]], encourages future young Bar\u00e7a players by saying \"With effort and sacrifice, you can also make it. Just do it, it is worth it!\".]]\n{{Quotation|\"The player who has passed through La Masia has something different to the rest, it's a plus that only comes from having competed in a Barcelona shirt from the time you were a child.\"|Former Barcelona coach Pep Guardiola<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=786617.html |title=Bar\u00e7a kids at home at La Masia|publisher=UEFA |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref>}}\nFormer technical director Pep Segura attributes the club's success to its \"philosophy of play\": \"It is about creating one philosophy, one mentality, from the bottom of the club to the top\". The philosophy consists of the application of [[total football]] mixed with traditional Spanish one-touch play (''tiqui-taka''). The total football approach was derived from the Netherlands football team through Cruyff.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> The total football approach requires the players to move in a fluid formation, where players can interchange positions quickly. In the youth academy, there is a large focus on technical ability, which is seen as a pre-requisite for inter-changes.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/><ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 74</ref> An often-quoted reason for Barcelona's success is the continuity and commitment with which Barcelona follow the current philosophy of pass and move. Guardiola was the prototype of the pivotal midfielder; famous midfielders Xavi and Iniesta are its custodians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/24/andres-iniesta-champions-league-barcelona-manchester-united |title=Andr\u00e9s Iniesta graduates from cameo role to take centre stage at Barcelona |work=Guardian |date=24 May 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2010 |author=Lowe, Sid}}</ref>\n\nAnother aspect of La Masia is its marked Catalan national character\u2014local talent in the service of a club with a strong, defining sense of the cultural make-up of Catalonia.<ref name=\"timesonline1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article1083027.ece |title=Fame academy |author=Hawkey, Ian |publisher=The Times |date=14 May 2006 }} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:New Masia building, at the Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper.jpg|thumb|left|The new Masia residence, opened in 2011 at the [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]].]]\nIn 2009, Messi became the first player from La Masia to be awarded with the [[Ballon d'Or]] prize for the best footballer in Europe, and the [[FIFA World Player]] award, for the best footballer in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20091201/53835120520/noticia/messi-primer-balon-de-oro-de-la-masia-del-barsa.html |title=Messi, primer Bal\u00f3n de Oro de la Masia del Bar\u00e7a |publisher=El Mundo Deportivo |date=1 December 2009 |author=Pellicer, Miquel |accessdate=27 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920145525/http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20091201/53835120520/noticia/messi-primer-balon-de-oro-de-la-masia-del-barsa.html |archivedate=September 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n[[Spain national football team|Spain]] won the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] with seven players from Barcelona in a World Cup final.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/gallery/spain-2010-world-cup-final-team-070810</ref>Joachim L\u00f6w, coach of Germany, said after his side's defeat by Spain that the opposition had a distinct Barcelona style: \"You can see it in every pass, how Spain plays is how Barcelona plays. They can hardly be beaten. They are extremely confident and very calm in the way they circulate the ball.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/10/sports/soccer/10iht-WCSOCCER.html|title=Talent to Spare, but There\u2019s Only One Trophy|first=Rob|last=Hughes|date=9 July 2010|work=New York Times|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2012, for the first time, Barcelona fielded all eleven players that have come up through La Masia in a La Liga match. After [[Dani Alves]] was substituted by [[Mart\u00edn Montoya]] due to an injury in the 13th minute,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2012-2013/dani-alves-pulls-hamstring-cannot-finish-match-against-levante |title=Dani Alves gives way to a La Masia all-eleven. |publisher=FCBarcelona.com |date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Bar\u00e7a played the next 60 minutes with [[V\u00edctor Vald\u00e9s]], [[Jordi Alba]], [[Carles Puyol]], [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]], Montoya, Busquets, Xavi, Iniesta, [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]], [[Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)|Pedro]], and Messi.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2012-2013/levante-fc-barcelona-masia-alumni-put-four-past-levante |title=La Masia puts four past Levante. |publisher=FCBarcelona.com |date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=decline/>\n\nIn the years immediately following this achievement, with those players aging and Barcelona seeking to maintain their position as one of the world's top clubs, they moved towards a more conventional recruitment strategy, signing some of the most talented players from around the globe for large transfer fees, such as [[Neymar]],<ref name=decline/> [[Luis Su\u00e1rez]] and [[Philippe Coutinho]], plus younger players (most with origins in Brazil and France) expected to improve further with the club; however, this approach (combined with something of a 'stockpiling' of players due to a transfer ban for breaching regulations regarding the signing of non-[[European Union|EU]] youth players)<ref name=decline/> meant there was less opportunity for local academy graduates to appear with the first team, and a perception that the quality of players produced by Barcelona was not quite as high as the previous generation.<ref name=decline>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/these-football-times/2015/jul/16/barcelona-la-masia-academy-decline-neymar-pedro|title=Is Barcelona's famed La Masia academy in decline? |website=These Football Times|author=James Robinson|via=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 July 2015 |accessdate=24 February 2019 }}</ref> Nevertheless, the team continued to win trophies and some further ''canteranos'' did make a breakthrough into the squad, including [[Rafinha (footballer, born February 1993)|Rafinha]],  [[Carles Ale\u00f1\u00e1]] and [[Sergi Roberto]], the latter having to retrain as a right back due to the abundance of talent in his original midfield position.<ref name=decline/>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:PepGuardiola.jpg|thumb|left| [[FC Barcelona#2008\u20132012: Guardiola era|Pep Guardiola's reign at Barcelona]] (2008\u20132012) marked one of the most successful eras in the history of the club and its youth academy.<ref>Hunter, Graham (September 2012). ''Bar\u00e7a: The Making of the Greatest Team in the World'', 2nd revised edition. (BackPage Press, {{ISBN|9780956497154}})</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/may/24/great-european-cup-teams-barcelona |author=Lowe, Sid |title=The great European Cup teams: Barcelona 2009\u20132011 |work=The Guardian |date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=24 August 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"D\u00faniaMart\u00ednUEFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2218180.html#barcas+tiki+taka+peak |author=Mart\u00edn, D\u00fania |title=The greatest teams of all time: Barcelona 2008\u201312 |publisher=UEFA.com |date=11 July 2015 |accessdate=21 August 2016 }}</ref>]]\n[[File:LeoMessi.JPG|thumb|upright|As Guardiola (2016) mentioned, Messi \u2013 with all his qualities \u2013 is considered as the best [[alumnus]] of Cruyffian (Bar\u00e7ajax) school of football.<ref name=\"SPORT.es\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sport-english.com/en/news/barca/pep-guardiola-cruyffs-legacy-infinite-5003949 |title=Pep Guardiola: Cruyff's legacy is infinite, we will never forget him |publisher=SPORT.es |date=25 March 2016 |accessdate=25 September 2016 }}</ref>]]\n\nMany players from Barcelona's youth system go on to have careers in football, whether at Barcelona or at other clubs. The following is a list of players who have played at least 100 league matches with the first team.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!style=\"width:11em\"|Name!!Nationality!!Position{{ref label|Positions|NB|}}!!Barcelona career!!Appearances!!Goals\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname||Xavi}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1998\u20132015||{{sort|505|505}}||{{sort|058|58}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Andr\u00e9s|Iniesta}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||2002\u20132018||{{sort|442|435}}||{{sort|035|35}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Lionel|Messi}}||align=\"left\"|{{ARG}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||2004\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|414|414}}||{{sort|378|378}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Carles|Puyol}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1999\u20132014||{{sort|392|392}}||{{sort|012|12}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|V\u00edctor|Vald\u00e9s}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]||2002\u20132014||{{sort|387|387}}||{{sort|000|0}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Guillermo|Amor}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1988\u20131998||{{sort|311|311}}||{{sort|047|47}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Sergio|Busquets}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||2008\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|305|305}}||{{sort|007|7}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Gerard|Piqu\u00e9}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||2008\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|270|270}}||{{sort|023|23}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Sergi|Barju\u00e1n}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1993\u20132002||{{sort|267|267}}||{{sort|006|6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Pep|Guardiola}} ||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1990\u20132001||{{sort|263|263}}||{{sort|006|6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Francisco|Carrasco}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||1978\u20131989||{{sort|262|262}}||{{sort|049|49}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Tente|S\u00e1nchez|Jos\u00e9 Vicente S\u00e1nchez|Sanchez, Tente}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1976\u20131986||{{sort|236|236}}||{{sort|016|16}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname||Pedro|Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||2007\u20132015||{{sort|204|204}}||{{sort|058|58}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Albert|Ferrer}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1990\u20131998||{{sort|204|204}}||{{sort|001|1}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Antonio|Olmo}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1976\u20131984||{{sort|188|188}}||{{sort|004|4}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Jordi|Alba}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||2012\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|155|155}}||{{sort|006|6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Gabri|Garc\u00eda}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1999\u20132006||{{sort|129|129}}||{{sort|007|7}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Oleguer|Presas}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||2001\u20132008||{{sort|127|127}}||{{sort|001|1}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Sergi|Roberto}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||2010\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|121|121}}||{{sort|001|1}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Ram\u00f3n|Calder\u00e9}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1984\u20131988||{{sort|110|110}}||{{sort|015|15}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Bojan|Krki\u0107}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||2007\u20132011||{{sort|104|104}}||{{sort|026|26}}\n|-\n|}\n\n*'''Bold''' denotes players still playing in [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n\n==References==\n;Bibliographies\n*{{cite book|title=Coaching youth soccer: the European model|first=Kevin|last=McShane|publisher=McFarland|year=2002|isbn=0-7864-1088-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/coachingyouthsoc00kevi}}\n* [[Mart\u00ed Perarnau]], ''Senda de campeones : De La Mas\u00eda al Camp Nou'', 10 Books (Grup 62), 2011.\n\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.uefa.com/trainingground/grassroots/video/videoid=1893330.html?autoplay=true Barcelona's talent factory (video)]\n* [https://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/01/15/the-academy-spotlight-ajax-and-barcelona/ The academy spotlight: Ajax and Barcelona] \u2013 ''These Football Times'' (2015)\n\n{{FC Barcelona}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Football academies in Spain]]\n[[Category:Les Corts (district)]]\n[[Category:Johan Cruyff]]\n[[Category:1702 establishments in Spain]]\n\n[[he:\u05d1\u05e8\u05e6\u05dc\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d1'#\u05dc\u05d4 \u05de\u05d0\u05e1\u05d9\u05d4]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|a type of rural construction common to the Catalan Countries|Masia}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                 = La Masia de Can Planes\n| alternate_names      = La Masia\n| image                = La Masia (Can Planas) (Barcelona) - 1.jpg\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = Main fa\u00e7ade of La Masia\n| map_type             =Spain\n| map_alt              =\n| map_caption          = Location within [[Spain]]\n| owner                = [[FC Barcelona]]\n| location_city        = [[Barcelona]]\n| location_country     =  Spain\n| coordinates          = {{coord|41.3831|N|2.1231|E|region:ES-CT_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date           =\n| completion_date      = 1702\n| inauguration_date    =\n| renovation_date      = 1966\n}}\n\n'''La Masia de Can Planes''', usually shortened to '''La Masia''' ({{IPA-ca|l\u0259 m\u0259\u02c8zi.\u0259}}; {{lang-en|\"The Farmhouse\"}}),<ref name=\"scholastic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.scholastic.com/browse/article.jsp?id=3754451 |title=School of Soccer Champions |publisher=Scholastic |author=Price, Sean |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> is a term used for [[FC Barcelona]]'s [[youth academy]]. The academy includes more than 300 young players. It has been a significant factor in Barcelona's European success, and produced some world class players in the early 2000s.\n\nIn 2010, La Masia became the first youth academy to have trained all three finalists for the [[FIFA Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]] in a single year - [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], [[Lionel Messi]] and [[Xavi]].<ref name=\"3players\">totalbarca.com, [http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/its-an-all-barca-affair-at-fifa-ballon-dor/ It\u2019s an all Bar\u00e7a affair at FIFA Ballon d\u2019Or] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210060409/http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/its-an-all-barca-affair-at-fifa-ballon-dor/ |date=December 10, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nLa Masia is also the name of FC Barcelona's football training facilities, originally located near the [[Camp Nou]] in the [[District of Les Corts|Les Corts]] district of [[Barcelona]]. The original building itself was an ancient country residence (In [[Catalan language|Catalan]]: [[masia]]) built in 1702, and once Camp Nou was inaugurated in 1957, the building was remodelled and extended for use as the club's social headquarters. With the gradual expansion of the club, the building became too small for headquarters, and on 20 October 1979, La Masia was converted into a dormitory for young players from outside Barcelona. On 30 June 2011, the Masia building ceased housing the academy players. In a simple ceremony, the doors were closed and the [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]] took over the function of the residential center for the players.\n\n==History==\n{{Johan Cruyff series}}\n[[File:Johan Cruijff 2013 Catalonia.jpg|thumb|right|[[Johan Cruyff]] in 2013. In [[Xavi]]'s words (2016), \"Cruyff established a very clear philosophy at Barcelona, he gave birth to that philosophy, he created Bar\u00e7a's DNA.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.as.com/en/2016/05/02/football/1462198310_725250.html |author=Jim\u00e9nez, Mayca |title=Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez critical of Atl\u00e9tico Madrid's playing style |publisher=AS.com (Diario AS) |date=2 May 2016 |accessdate=22 August 2016 }}</ref> La Masia's coaching system is often considered as the foremost bastion of Cruyffian (Bar\u00e7ajax) school of football.]]\nLa Masia de Can Planes was an old Catalan farmhouse, built in 1702. In 1979, it was first used by the club to house its young footballers who originated from outside Barcelona.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite web|last=Rogers |first=Iain |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE59L02D20091022 |title=Barca talent farm marks 30 years of success |publisher=Reuters |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> The idea for the youth academy was proposed to N\u00fa\u00f1ez by Jaume Amat<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD03/PUB/2009/10/21/EMD20091021022MDP.pdf|title=La Mas\u00eda naci\u00f3 en un minuto |publisher=Mundo Deportivo |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>, and Oriol Tort was put in charge of the facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w2.bcn.cat/bcnmetropolis/en/calaixera/biografies/oriol-tort-lanima-de-la-masia-del-barca/|title=Oriol Tort, the soul of Bar\u00e7a\u2019s Masia|last=Genis Sinca|work=Barcelona Metropolis|publisher=Ayuntament de Barcelona|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, it was announced that Barcelona would be moving all its football training activities to La [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/inside-ciutat-esportiva-joan-gamper/|title=Inside : Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper|date=29 September 2011|publisher=Inside Spanish Football|accessdate=11 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130629125931/http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/inside-ciutat-esportiva-joan-gamper/|archivedate=29 June 2013}} </ref>\n\nLa Masia received more publicity after Barcelona B's success with homegrown players; Rory Smith reported in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that La Masia \"has replaced the fabled [[Ajax Academy]] as football's foremost production line\".<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Rory |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup-2010/teams/spain/7895208/World-Cup-2010-Spains-battle-won-on-the-playing-fields-of-Barcelona.html |title=World Cup 2010: Spain's battle won on the playing fields of Barcelona |publisher=Telegraph |date=17 July 2010 |accessdate=20 August 2010}}</ref> The recent fame and success of La Masia as a talent school was ascribed by Ian Hawkey of ''[[The Times]]'' to the class of 1987, which featured prominent members such as [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]], [[Lionel Messi]], [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]] and [[Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)|Pedro]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/european_football/article7078610.ece |author=Hawkey, Ian |publisher=The Times |date=28 March 2010 |title=Friends reunited: Cesc Fabregas and the class of 1987 |accessdate=30 July 2010}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In 2000, [[Louis van Gaal]], coach of Barcelona's first team, was widely ridiculed by the city sports media for his dream to win the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] with 11&nbsp;home-grown players. The first team won the trophy in 2009 with eight home-grown players.<ref name=\"sport1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sport.es/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=44&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=724176&idseccio_PK=803 |title=La Masia, como un laboratorio |publisher=SPORT.es |accessdate=19 August 2010 |language=Spanish |author=Perarnau, Mart\u00ed |date=18 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=February 2013}}{{cbignore}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979 to 2009, 440&nbsp;youngsters have left their homes and families to stay at the academy. About half of them were from [[Catalonia]], and the rest came from other regions of the [[Kingdom of Spain]] and beyond, including 15 from [[Cameroon]], 7 from [[Brazil]], 5 from [[Senegal]] and 3 from [[Argentina]]. Of those 440, 40&nbsp;made it into Barcelona's first team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKLO72065620090525 |first=Iain |last=Rogers |title=INTERVIEW-Soccer-La Masia a fertile breeding ground for Barca |publisher=Reuters |date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nLa Masia houses about 60 players: 10 in the farmhouse, and the rest in rooms of the adjacent stadium; the rest of the youth players must provide for their own accommodation.<ref name=\"reuters1\"/><ref name=\"dailymail1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1261064/Lionel-Messi-Cesc-Fabregas-Gerard-Pique--forged-Barcelonas-hothouse-champions.html |title=Lionel Messi, Cesc Fabregas, Gerard Pique... all forged in Barcelona's hothouse of champions |author=Kay, Alex |publisher=Daily Mail |date=27 March 2010 |accessdate=27 August 2010}}</ref>\nThe academy is one of the most expensive in Europe, operating at a cost of \u00a35&nbsp;million a year. The main cost is the dormitory, La Masia itself.<ref name=\"dailymail1\"/> The minimum age for the youth program is six years; each year, more than 1,000&nbsp;boys from the ages of six to eight try out for admittance. The best 200 are selected.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 39</ref> The club also actively seeks for prospective students; it employs a system in which 15&nbsp;scouts are deployed in Catalonia, 15 in the rest of Spain and 10 scattered throughout the world. To alleviate the expenses of this scouting, the club has an agreement with 15 local clubs for them to train players who are not ready for entry into the youth academy. In return, FC Barcelona gives money, coaching and technical advice to these clubs for their services.<ref name=mcshane53>McShane, Kevin. p. 53</ref> While expanding its operations abroad, the club established five schools in Mexico and one in Egypt; successful applicants to these schools become full-time students, receiving academic education and football training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/futbol/futbol_base/FCBEscola/FCBEscola.html |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091003160049/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/futbol/futbol_base/FCBEscola/FCBEscola.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 October 2009 |title=FCBEscola |publisher=FC Barcelona |accessdate=14 August 2010 }}</ref>\n[[File:S. Busquets (2009-05).jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Sergio Busquets]], a graduate of La Masia, has been a part of the Barcelona first team since 2008.]]\n\nWhen Guardiola re-organised the reserve side, he set up a three-staged program to formalise the advancement from Juvenil to Barcelona B and finally to the first team. The first stage of a youth player's career involves a rotation scheme with Barcelona B. The second stage involves making the player aware of his importance to the team and the expectation that the player will improve cohesion and performance within the reserve side. In the last stage, he is designated a \"key\" player of the B team and might be called to the first team. One of the players in the third phase is made captain, regardless of the experience of older players.<ref name=\"sport1\"/>\n\nThe teams at Barcelona play from August to May; mild weather at La baks allows players to train outdoors throughout the year. The youth teams train after school; Barcelona B plays  as a professional team, training in the morning and evening.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 74-79</ref> All of the trainers at FC Barcelona are former professional footballers.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 105</ref>\n\n[[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]], the club's main youth team, and the 12 other youth teams contained 24 coaches and more than 300 players. There are 56 other employees, including doctors, psychologists, nutritionists, cooks and physiologists.<ref name=\"dailymail1\"/> In the 2009\u201310 season, the B team qualified for the Segunda Divisi\u00f3n again. Barcelona B play in a 4\u20133\u20133 [[Formation (association football)|formation]], which is the same formation employed by the first team.<ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 77</ref>\n\n==Philosophy==\n[[File:Masia-AmorFerrerMussonsGuardiola.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Guillermo Amor]], [[Albert Ferrer]], Josep Mussons (Bar\u00e7a Vice-president) and [[Pep Guardiola]]. This photo was displayed for many years at the entrance of La Masia dining room. Their signature, in [[Catalan language]], encourages future young Bar\u00e7a players by saying \"With effort and sacrifice, you can also make it. Just do it, it is worth it!\".]]\n{{Quotation|\"The player who has passed through La Masia has something different to the rest, it's a plus that only comes from having competed in a Barcelona shirt from the time you were a child.\"|Former Barcelona coach Pep Guardiola<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=786617.html |title=Bar\u00e7a kids at home at La Masia|publisher=UEFA |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref>}}\nFormer technical director Pep Segura attributes the club's success to its \"philosophy of play\": \"It is about creating one philosophy, one mentality, from the bottom of the club to the top\". The philosophy consists of the application of [[total football]] mixed with traditional Spanish one-touch play (''tiqui-taka''). The total football approach was derived from the Netherlands football team through Cruyff.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> The total football approach requires the players to move in a fluid formation, where players can interchange positions quickly. In the youth academy, there is a large focus on technical ability, which is seen as a pre-requisite for inter-changes.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/><ref>McShane, Kevin. p. 74</ref> An often-quoted reason for Barcelona's success is the continuity and commitment with which Barcelona follow the current philosophy of pass and move. Guardiola was the prototype of the pivotal midfielder; famous midfielders Xavi and Iniesta are its custodians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/24/andres-iniesta-champions-league-barcelona-manchester-united |title=Andr\u00e9s Iniesta graduates from cameo role to take centre stage at Barcelona |work=Guardian |date=24 May 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2010 |author=Lowe, Sid}}</ref>\n\nAnother aspect of La Masia is its marked Catalan national character\u2014local talent in the service of a club with a strong, defining sense of the cultural make-up of Catalonia.<ref name=\"timesonline1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article1083027.ece |title=Fame academy |author=Hawkey, Ian |publisher=The Times |date=14 May 2006 }} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n[[File:New Masia building, at the Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper.jpg|thumb|left|The new Masia residence, opened in 2011 at the [[Ciutat Esportiva Joan Gamper]].]]\nIn 2009, Messi became the first player from La Masia to be awarded with the [[Ballon d'Or]] prize for the best footballer in Europe, and the [[FIFA World Player]] award, for the best footballer in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20091201/53835120520/noticia/messi-primer-balon-de-oro-de-la-masia-del-barsa.html |title=Messi, primer Bal\u00f3n de Oro de la Masia del Bar\u00e7a |publisher=El Mundo Deportivo |date=1 December 2009 |author=Pellicer, Miquel |accessdate=27 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920145525/http://www.elmundodeportivo.es/gen/20091201/53835120520/noticia/messi-primer-balon-de-oro-de-la-masia-del-barsa.html |archivedate=September 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n[[Spain national football team|Spain]] won the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] with seven players from Barcelona in a World Cup final.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/gallery/spain-2010-world-cup-final-team-070810</ref>Joachim L\u00f6w, coach of Germany, said after his side's defeat by Spain that the opposition had a distinct Barcelona style: \"You can see it in every pass, how Spain plays is how Barcelona plays. They can hardly be beaten. They are extremely confident and very calm in the way they circulate the ball.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/10/sports/soccer/10iht-WCSOCCER.html|title=Talent to Spare, but There\u2019s Only One Trophy|first=Rob|last=Hughes|date=9 July 2010|work=New York Times|accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2012, for the first time, Barcelona fielded all eleven players that have come up through La Masia in a La Liga match. After [[Dani Alves]] was substituted by [[Mart\u00edn Montoya]] due to an injury in the 13th minute,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2012-2013/dani-alves-pulls-hamstring-cannot-finish-match-against-levante |title=Dani Alves gives way to a La Masia all-eleven. |publisher=FCBarcelona.com |date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> Bar\u00e7a played the next 60 minutes with [[V\u00edctor Vald\u00e9s]], [[Jordi Alba]], [[Carles Puyol]], [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]], Montoya, Busquets, Xavi, Iniesta, [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]], [[Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)|Pedro]], and Messi.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2012-2013/levante-fc-barcelona-masia-alumni-put-four-past-levante |title=La Masia puts four past Levante. |publisher=FCBarcelona.com |date=25 November 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=decline/>\n\nIn the years immediately following this achievement, with those players aging and Barcelona seeking to maintain their position as one of the world's top clubs, they moved towards a more conventional recruitment strategy, signing some of the most talented players from around the globe for large transfer fees, such as [[Neymar]],<ref name=decline/> [[Luis Su\u00e1rez]] and [[Philippe Coutinho]], plus younger players (most with origins in Brazil and France) expected to improve further with the club; however, this approach (combined with something of a 'stockpiling' of players due to a transfer ban for breaching regulations regarding the signing of non-[[European Union|EU]] youth players)<ref name=decline/> meant there was less opportunity for local academy graduates to appear with the first team, and a perception that the quality of players produced by Barcelona was not quite as high as the previous generation.<ref name=decline>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/these-football-times/2015/jul/16/barcelona-la-masia-academy-decline-neymar-pedro|title=Is Barcelona's famed La Masia academy in decline? |website=These Football Times|author=James Robinson|via=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 July 2015 |accessdate=24 February 2019 }}</ref> Nevertheless, the team continued to win trophies and some further ''canteranos'' did make a breakthrough into the squad, including [[Rafinha (footballer, born February 1993)|Rafinha]],  [[Carles Ale\u00f1\u00e1]] and [[Sergi Roberto]], the latter having to retrain as a right back due to the abundance of talent in his original midfield position.<ref name=decline/>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n[[File:PepGuardiola.jpg|thumb|left| [[FC Barcelona#2008\u20132012: Guardiola era|Pep Guardiola's reign at Barcelona]] (2008\u20132012) marked one of the most successful eras in the history of the club and its youth academy.<ref>Hunter, Graham (September 2012). ''Bar\u00e7a: The Making of the Greatest Team in the World'', 2nd revised edition. (BackPage Press, {{ISBN|9780956497154}})</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/may/24/great-european-cup-teams-barcelona |author=Lowe, Sid |title=The great European Cup teams: Barcelona 2009\u20132011 |work=The Guardian |date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=24 August 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"D\u00faniaMart\u00ednUEFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2218180.html#barcas+tiki+taka+peak |author=Mart\u00edn, D\u00fania |title=The greatest teams of all time: Barcelona 2008\u201312 |publisher=UEFA.com |date=11 July 2015 |accessdate=21 August 2016 }}</ref>]]\n[[File:LeoMessi.JPG|thumb|upright|As Guardiola (2016) mentioned, Messi \u2013 with all his qualities \u2013 is considered as the best [[alumnus]] of Cruyffian (Bar\u00e7ajax) school of football.<ref name=\"SPORT.es\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sport-english.com/en/news/barca/pep-guardiola-cruyffs-legacy-infinite-5003949 |title=Pep Guardiola: Cruyff's legacy is infinite, we will never forget him |publisher=SPORT.es |date=25 March 2016 |accessdate=25 September 2016 }}</ref>]]\n\nMany players from Barcelona's youth system go on to have careers in football, whether at Barcelona or at other clubs. The following is a list of players who have played at least 100 league matches with the first team.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!style=\"width:11em\"|Name!!Nationality!!Position{{ref label|Positions|NB|}}!!Barcelona career!!Appearances!!Goals\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname||Xavi}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1998\u20132015||{{sort|505|505}}||{{sort|058|58}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Andr\u00e9s|Iniesta}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||2002\u20132018||{{sort|442|435}}||{{sort|035|35}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Lionel|Messi}}||align=\"left\"|{{ARG}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||2004\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|414|414}}||{{sort|378|378}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Carles|Puyol}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1999\u20132014||{{sort|392|392}}||{{sort|012|12}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|V\u00edctor|Vald\u00e9s}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]||2002\u20132014||{{sort|387|387}}||{{sort|000|0}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Guillermo|Amor}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1988\u20131998||{{sort|311|311}}||{{sort|047|47}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Sergio|Busquets}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||2008\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|305|305}}||{{sort|007|7}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Gerard|Piqu\u00e9}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||2008\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|270|270}}||{{sort|023|23}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Sergi|Barju\u00e1n}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1993\u20132002||{{sort|267|267}}||{{sort|006|6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Pep|Guardiola}} ||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1990\u20132001||{{sort|263|263}}||{{sort|006|6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Francisco|Carrasco}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||1978\u20131989||{{sort|262|262}}||{{sort|049|49}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Tente|S\u00e1nchez|Jos\u00e9 Vicente S\u00e1nchez|Sanchez, Tente}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1976\u20131986||{{sort|236|236}}||{{sort|016|16}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname||Pedro|Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||2007\u20132015||{{sort|204|204}}||{{sort|058|58}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Albert|Ferrer}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1990\u20131998||{{sort|204|204}}||{{sort|001|1}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Antonio|Olmo}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||1976\u20131984||{{sort|188|188}}||{{sort|004|4}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Jordi|Alba}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||2012\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|155|155}}||{{sort|006|6}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Gabri|Garc\u00eda}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1999\u20132006||{{sort|129|129}}||{{sort|007|7}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Oleguer|Presas}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Defender (association football)|Defender]]||2001\u20132008||{{sort|127|127}}||{{sort|001|1}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''{{sortname|Sergi|Roberto}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||2010\u2013 \u00a4||{{sort|121|121}}||{{sort|001|1}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Ram\u00f3n|Calder\u00e9}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Midfielder]]||1984\u20131988||{{sort|110|110}}||{{sort|015|15}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Bojan|Krki\u0107}}||align=\"left\"|{{ESP}}||[[Forward (association football)|Forward]]||2007\u20132011||{{sort|104|104}}||{{sort|026|26}}\n|-\n|}\n\n*'''Bold''' denotes players still playing in [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n\n==References==\n;Bibliographies\n*{{cite book|title=Coaching youth soccer: the European model|first=Kevin|last=McShane|publisher=McFarland|year=2002|isbn=0-7864-1088-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/coachingyouthsoc00kevi}}\n* [[Mart\u00ed Perarnau]], ''Senda de campeones : De La Mas\u00eda al Camp Nou'', 10 Books (Grup 62), 2011.\n\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.uefa.com/trainingground/grassroots/video/videoid=1893330.html?autoplay=true Barcelona's talent factory (video)]\n* [https://thesefootballtimes.co/2015/01/15/the-academy-spotlight-ajax-and-barcelona/ The academy spotlight: Ajax and Barcelona] \u2013 ''These Football Times'' (2015)\n\n{{FC Barcelona}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Barcelona]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Football academies in Spain]]\n[[Category:Les Corts (district)]]\n[[Category:Johan Cruyff]]\n[[Category:1702 establishments in Spain]]\n\n[[he:\u05d1\u05e8\u05e6\u05dc\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d1'#\u05dc\u05d4 \u05de\u05d0\u05e1\u05d9\u05d4]]\n", "name_user": "Soifam", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Masia"}
{"title_page": "Lil' Kleine", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Lil kleine jorik scholten-1518018394.jpg\n| image_upright      = 1.2\n| caption            = Lil' Kleine in 2017\n| birth_name         = Jorik Scholten\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1994|10|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* actor}}\n| years_active       = 2005\u2013present\n| partner            = Jaimie Vaes\n| children           = 1\n| website            = {{URL|lilkleine.nl}}\n| module             =\n  {{Infobox musical artist | embed=yes\n  | background          = solo_singer\n  | genre               = [[Nederhop]]\n  | instrument          = Vocals\n  | label               = [[TopNotch]]\n  | associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Broederliefde]]\n* [[Boef]]\n* [[Danny de Munk]]\n* [[Ronnie Flex]]}}\n  }}\n}}\n'''Jorik Scholten''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8j\u0254r\u026ak sx\u0254lt\u0259n}}; born 15 October 1994), professionally known as '''Lil' Kleine''' ({{IPA-nl|l\u026al \u02c8kl\u025bi\u032fn\u0259|pron}}), is a Dutch musician and actor. He collaborated with fellow rapper [[Ronnie Flex]] to produce the [[List of best-selling singles|number one single]] \"[[Drank & Drugs]]\" and the [[List of best-selling albums|number one album]] ''[[WOP!]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===1994\u20132013: Early life and career beginnings===\nScholten was born on 15 October 1994 in the [[Nieuwmarkt]] district of Amsterdam, Netherlands. At the age of one, he was diagnosed with [[leukemia]] in his back that required surgery.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lilkleine.nl|title=Lil' Kleine \u2013 Offici\u00eble website|website=www.lilkleine.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref> He spent the first seven years of his life in [[De Wallen]], moving to [[Amsterdam-Oost]] with his father after his parents divorced.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/3AlRiyjMywTVNzTcHbf9QT|title=Lil' Kleine|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nScholten was signed with talent agencies at an early age and made his acting debut in the 2005 film ''[[Diep]]''. After befriending rapper [[Lange Frans]], he began performing with Lange Frans' band [[D-Men]] on-stage. In 2012, he adopted the stage name \"Lil' Kleine\" and released his first EP, \"Tuig van de Richel\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dewerelddraaitdoor.bnnvara.nl/gasten/lil-kleine?npo_cc=126&|title=Lil' Kleine|website=[[BNNVARA]]|language=nl-NL|access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref> The following year, the song \"Zo Verdomd Alleen\", which he recorded with [[Danny de Munk]], reached the [[Single Top 100]].\n\n===2013\u2013present: \"Drank & Drugs\", ''WOP!'', ''Alleen'' and other endeavours===\nAfter signing with hip-hop label [[TopNotch]] in 2013, he collaborated with fellow rapper [[Ronnie Flex]] to produce the single \"[[Drank & Drugs]]\", a song about alcohol, drugs and sex, which reached number one on the Single Top 100 and was [[Music recording sales certification|certified]] double platinum.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \"Drank & Drugs\" won the [[NPO 3FM#3FM Awards|3FM Award]] for Best Single in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npo3fm.nl/nieuws/3fm/373902-dit-zijn-de-winnaars-van-de-3fm-awards?npo_cc=126&|title=Dit zijn de winnaars van de 3FM Awards|website=NPO 3FM|language=nl-nl|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Lil' Kleine released his debut album ''[[WOP!]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the album\u2019s first week, all eleven of its tracks ranked within the top 35 of the Single Top 100 and the album reached number 1 on the [[Album Top 100]] \u2013 it is the first hip hop/rap album in the Netherlands to accomplish these feats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://3voor12.vpro.nl/artikelen/overzicht/2016/Februari/lil-kleine-wop-nummer-1-album-single-top-100.html|title=Lil' Kleine breekt records: heel WOP in de Single Top 100 \u2013 stories|work=[[3VOOR12]]|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl-NL}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nu.nl/muziek/4217564/lil-kleine-breekt-meerdere-records-in-nederlandse-hitlijsten.html|title=Lil' Kleine breekt meerdere records in Nederlandse hitlijsten|work=[[NU.nl]]|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref> ''WOP!'' also became the most-streamed new album on [[Spotify]] in Dutch history, being streamed over 1.5 million times during the 24 hours after its release, beating the previous record holder, [[Justin Bieber]]'s ''[[Purpose (Justin Bieber album)|Purpose]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.puna.nl/lil-kleine-breekt-records-met-debuutalbum-wop/|title=Lil Kleine breekt records met debuutalbum WOP|date=15 February 2016|work=www.puna.nl|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.metronieuws.nl/nieuws/showbizz/2016/02/lil-kleine-breekt-records-met-debuutalbum-wop|title=Lil&#039; Kleine breekt records met debuutalbum WOP|work=Metronieuws|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Also in its first week, all of the album\u2019s tracks ranked within Spotify's Netherlands Top 50, with singles \"Niet Omdat Het Moet\" and \"1, 2, 3\" (both featuring Ronnie Flex) at numbers 1 and 2 respectively.<ref name=\":3\" /> \"Niet Omdat Het Moet\" received over half a million views on [[YouTube]] during its first few days, being the most viewed YouTube video in the Netherlands at the time.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nLil' Kleine\u2019s second album, ''Alleen'', was released in May 2017. All eleven of its tracks reached Spotify's Netherlands Top 25, with songs \"Krantenwijk\" (featuring [[Boef]]) and \"Alleen\" at numbers 1 and 2 respectively. Collectively, Lil' Kleine\u2019s songs were streamed by 1.84 million listeners on Spotify during the month preceding the album\u2019s release \u2013 the first time an individual Dutch artist\u2019s music was streamed by that many listeners in the space of a month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.puna.nl/lil-kleine-breekt-records-met-zijn-nieuwe-album-alleen/|title=Lil Kleine breekt records met zijn nieuwe album Alleen|date=29 May 2017|work=www.puna.nl|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://top-notch.nl/nieuws/lil-kleine-met-zijn-complete-album-in-de-top-25|title=Lil Kleine met zijn complete album in de top 25|work=TopNotch|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl-NL}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lil' Kleine was one of fifteen celebrities who competed on the [[Expeditie Robinson 2017|nineteenth season]] of ''[[Expeditie Robinson]]''. He was the first contestant to leave the competition, having been voted off at his own request after three days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nhnieuws.nl/nieuws/212077/Lil-Kleine-verlaat-als-eerste-Expeditie-Robinson|title=Lil' Kleine verlaat als eerste Expeditie Robinson|date=14 September 2017|work=NH Nieuws|access-date=9 April 2018|language=nl-NL}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Lil' Kleine became a coach on the [[The Voice of Holland (season 9)|ninth season]] of ''[[The Voice of Holland]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/rtlboulevard/lil-kleine-nieuwe-coach-the-voice|title=Lil' Kleine nieuwe coach The Voice|work=RTL Nieuws|date=16 February 2018|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Lil' Kleine released his third album, ''Jongen Van De Straat''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.funx.nl/news/music/46022-lil-kleine-breekt-spotify-record-met-album-jongen-van-de-straat?q=&start=&end=|title=Lil Kleine breekt Spotify-record met album 'Jongen van de Straat'|website=FunX.nl|language=nl-nl|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n==Personal life==\nLil' Kleine is engaged to Jaimie Vaes, and they have a son born in June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.destentor.nl/show/rapper-lil-kleine-voor-het-eerst-vader-geworden~ab9b337b/|title=Rapper Lil' Kleine voor het eerst vader geworden|last=Segers|first=Maxime|date=9 June 2019|website=De Stentor|access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[WOP!]]'' (2016)\n* ''Alleen'' (2017)\n* ''Jongen van de straat'' (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|lilkleine.nl}}\n* {{IMDb name|2072346|Jorik Scholten}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Lil' Kleine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lil' Kleine}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch rappers]]\n[[Category:Dutch male actors]]\n[[Category:Dutch male child actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch-language singers]]\n[[Category:Leukemia survivors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Lil kleine jorik scholten-1518018394.jpg\n| image_upright      = 1.2\n| caption            = Lil' Kleine in 2017\n| birth_name         = Jorik Scholten\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1994|10|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* actor}}\n| years_active       = 2005\u2013present\n| partner            = Jaimie Vaes\n| children           = 1\n| website            = {{URL|lilkleine.nl}}\n| module             =\n  {{Infobox musical artist | embed=yes\n  | background          = solo_singer\n  | genre               = [[Nederhop]]\n  | instrument          = Vocals\n  | label               = [[TopNotch]]\n  | associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Broederliefde]]\n* [[Boef]]\n* [[Danny de Munk]]\n* [[Ronnie Flex]]}}\n  }}\n}}\n'''Jorik Scholten''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8j\u0254r\u026ak sx\u0254lt\u0259n}}; born 15 October 1994), professionally known as '''Lil' Kleine''' ({{IPA-nl|l\u026al \u02c8kl\u025bi\u032fn\u0259|pron}}), is a Dutch musician and actor. He collaborated with fellow rapper [[Ronnie Flex]] to produce the [[List of best-selling singles|number one single]] \"[[Drank & Drugs]]\" and the [[List of best-selling albums|number one album]] ''[[WOP!]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===1994\u20132013: Early life and career beginnings===\nScholten was born on 15 October 1994 in the [[Nieuwmarkt]] district of Amsterdam, Netherlands. At the age of one, he was diagnosed with [[leukemia]] in his back that required surgery.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lilkleine.nl|title=Lil' Kleine \u2013 Offici\u00eble website|website=www.lilkleine.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref> He spent the first seven years of his life in [[De Wallen]], moving to [[Amsterdam-Oost]] with his father after his parents divorced.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/artist/3AlRiyjMywTVNzTcHbf9QT|title=Lil' Kleine|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nScholten was signed with talent agencies at an early age and made his acting debut in the 2005 film ''[[Diep]]''. After befriending rapper [[Lange Frans]], he began performing with Lange Frans' band [[D-Men]] on-stage. In 2012, he adopted the stage name \"Lil' Kleine\" and released his first EP, \"Tuig van de Richel\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dewerelddraaitdoor.bnnvara.nl/gasten/lil-kleine?npo_cc=126&|title=Lil' Kleine|website=[[BNNVARA]]|language=nl-NL|access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref> The following year, the song \"Zo Verdomd Alleen\", which he recorded with [[Danny de Munk]], reached the [[Single Top 100]].\n\n===2013\u2013present: \"Drank & Drugs\", ''WOP!'', ''Alleen'' and other endeavours===\nAfter signing with hip-hop label [[TopNotch]] in 2013, he collaborated with fellow rapper [[Ronnie Flex]] to produce the single \"[[Drank & Drugs]]\", a song about alcohol, drugs and sex, which reached number one on the Single Top 100 and was [[Music recording sales certification|certified]] double platinum.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \"Drank & Drugs\" won the [[NPO 3FM#3FM Awards|3FM Award]] for Best Single in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npo3fm.nl/nieuws/3fm/373902-dit-zijn-de-winnaars-van-de-3fm-awards?npo_cc=126&|title=Dit zijn de winnaars van de 3FM Awards|website=NPO 3FM|language=nl-nl|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Lil' Kleine released his debut album ''[[WOP!]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> In the album\u2019s first week, all eleven of its tracks ranked within the top 35 of the Single Top 100 and the album reached number 1 on the [[Album Top 100]] \u2013 it is the first hip hop/rap album in the Netherlands to accomplish these feats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://3voor12.vpro.nl/artikelen/overzicht/2016/Februari/lil-kleine-wop-nummer-1-album-single-top-100.html|title=Lil' Kleine breekt records: heel WOP in de Single Top 100 \u2013 stories|work=[[3VOOR12]]|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl-NL}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nu.nl/muziek/4217564/lil-kleine-breekt-meerdere-records-in-nederlandse-hitlijsten.html|title=Lil' Kleine breekt meerdere records in Nederlandse hitlijsten|work=[[NU.nl]]|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref> ''WOP!'' also became the most-streamed new album on [[Spotify]] in Dutch history, being streamed over 1.5 million times during the 24 hours after its release, beating the previous record holder, [[Justin Bieber]]'s ''[[Purpose (Justin Bieber album)|Purpose]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.puna.nl/lil-kleine-breekt-records-met-debuutalbum-wop/|title=Lil Kleine breekt records met debuutalbum WOP|date=15 February 2016|work=www.puna.nl|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.metronieuws.nl/nieuws/showbizz/2016/02/lil-kleine-breekt-records-met-debuutalbum-wop|title=Lil&#039; Kleine breekt records met debuutalbum WOP|work=Metronieuws|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Also in its first week, all of the album\u2019s tracks ranked within Spotify's Netherlands Top 50, with singles \"Niet Omdat Het Moet\" and \"1, 2, 3\" (both featuring Ronnie Flex) at numbers 1 and 2 respectively.<ref name=\":3\" /> \"Niet Omdat Het Moet\" received over half a million views on [[YouTube]] during its first few days, being the most viewed YouTube video in the Netherlands at the time.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nLil' Kleine\u2019s second album, ''Alleen'', was released in May 2017. All eleven of its tracks reached Spotify's Netherlands Top 25, with songs \"Krantenwijk\" (featuring [[Boef]]) and \"Alleen\" at numbers 1 and 2 respectively. Collectively, Lil' Kleine\u2019s songs were streamed by 1.84 million listeners on Spotify during the month preceding the album\u2019s release \u2013 the first time an individual Dutch artist\u2019s music was streamed by that many listeners in the space of a month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.puna.nl/lil-kleine-breekt-records-met-zijn-nieuwe-album-alleen/|title=Lil Kleine breekt records met zijn nieuwe album Alleen|date=29 May 2017|work=www.puna.nl|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://top-notch.nl/nieuws/lil-kleine-met-zijn-complete-album-in-de-top-25|title=Lil Kleine met zijn complete album in de top 25|work=TopNotch|access-date=6 November 2017|language=nl-NL}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lil' Kleine was one of fifteen celebrities who competed on the [[Expeditie Robinson 2017|nineteenth season]] of ''[[Expeditie Robinson]]''. He was the first contestant to leave the competition, having been voted off at his own request after three days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nhnieuws.nl/nieuws/212077/Lil-Kleine-verlaat-als-eerste-Expeditie-Robinson|title=Lil' Kleine verlaat als eerste Expeditie Robinson|date=14 September 2017|work=NH Nieuws|access-date=9 April 2018|language=nl-NL}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Lil' Kleine became a coach on the [[The Voice of Holland (season 9)|ninth season]] of ''[[The Voice of Holland]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/rtlboulevard/lil-kleine-nieuwe-coach-the-voice|title=Lil' Kleine nieuwe coach The Voice|work=RTL Nieuws|date=16 February 2018|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Lil' Kleine released his third album, ''Jongen Van De Straat''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.funx.nl/news/music/46022-lil-kleine-breekt-spotify-record-met-album-jongen-van-de-straat?q=&start=&end=|title=Lil Kleine breekt Spotify-record met album 'Jongen van de Straat'|website=FunX.nl|language=nl-nl|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n==Personal life==\nLil' Kleine is engaged to Jaimie Vaes, and they have a son born in June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.destentor.nl/show/rapper-lil-kleine-voor-het-eerst-vader-geworden~ab9b337b/|title=Rapper Lil' Kleine voor het eerst vader geworden|last=Segers|first=Maxime|date=9 June 2019|website=De Stentor|access-date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[WOP!]]'' (2016)\n* ''Alleen'' (2017)\n* ''Jongen Van De Straat'' (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|lilkleine.nl}}\n* {{IMDb name|2072346|Jorik Scholten}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Lil' Kleine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lil' Kleine}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch rappers]]\n[[Category:Dutch male actors]]\n[[Category:Dutch male child actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch-language singers]]\n[[Category:Leukemia survivors]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lil%27_Kleine"}
{"title_page": "Shelly Kishore", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shelly Kishore\n\n|image = {{CSS image crop\n|Image = Indian Panorama film 'Thanga Meenkal' Director cum Actor Ram with Actress Shelly Kishore interacting with the Media, at the 44th India International Film Festival of India (IFFI-2013), in Panaji, Goa on November 27, 2013..jpg\n|bSize = 500\n|cWidth = 220\n|cHeight = 200\n|oTop = 50\n|oLeft = 0\n|Location=center\n}}\n\n| caption            = Shelly Kishore at [[International Film Festival of India|IFFI]] [[44th International Film Festival of India|2013]] \n| birthname          = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|08|18}} \n| birth_place        = [[Dubai]], UAE \n| othername          = Shelly Nabu Kumar\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2006-2014<br/>2017 \u2013 present\n| parents            = J.Nabu Kumar and Sheela\n| spouse             = Kishore\n| children           = Yuvan Kishore\n| homepage           = \n| notable role       = \n}}\n'''Shelly Kishore''' is an Indian film and Television actress who is well known for her role in [[Kumkumapoovu]]. She received a [[Kerala state television award for best actress]] in 2006.\n\n==Early Life==\n\nShelly Kishore received the State Government award for the best actress in 2006 for her role in the serial \"Thaniye\", telecasted in [[Amritha]] TV. Shelly's first Malayalam movie was \"[[Kerala Cafe]]\", directed by [[Shankar Ramakrishnan]]. Shelly's first Tamil movie was \"[[Thanga Meenkal]]\", directed by [[Ram (director)|Ram]]. Shelly has got an opportunity to be a part of the Hindi movie \"[[The Waiting Room (2010 film)|The Waiting Room]]\", directed by [[Maneej Premnath]].<ref>http://ibnlive.in.com/videos/108656/thriller-the-waiting-room-to-release-on-friday.html</ref> She has learned Mohiniyattam, Kuchipudi and Bharatanatyam. Shelly was selected as the second runner up for the Miss Flower Show contest held at Kanakakunnu, Trivandrum.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/starry-dreams/article4576772.ece | title=Starry dreams | date=3 April 2013 | newspaper=The Hindu | first=Athira | last=M | accessdate=7 September 2019 }}</ref> Shelly's father, J. Nabu Kumar, is a civil engineer in Dubai, U.A.E. Her mother Sheela is a housewife. She has an elder brother and a sister. Shelly's brother is married and is settled in America. Her sister, Shibily works as a teacher.<ref>http://www.ukmalayalee.com/latest-news/news.php?id=MjgxNQ==</ref> Shelly has done her schooling in Muscat and in New Indian Model School, Dubai. She has a diploma in mass media and communication from Singapore and another diploma in sociology. Shelly has completed her Post Graduation in E-Governance.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/Kumkumappoovu</ref> Shelly has acted in the Malayalam movie \"Kanalkannadi\" directed by Jayan Poduval, it was never released.<ref>http://www.tamilplex.com/article/eng/2013/11/11/29/thanga-meenkal-tamil-movie-review.html</ref>\nShelly is very famous in Malayali households for her portrayal of Shalini rudran in Kumkumapoovu serial.After finishing kumkumapoovu she take a break from Television and In 2017 She come back Through the portrayal of Balasuda in Sthreepadam serial.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year !! Title !!    Role   !! Co-stars !!Director !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Kanal Kannadi'' ||Anamika ||[[Indrajith Sukumaran]], [[Karthika Mathew]]||Jayan Poduval ||[[Malayalam]]||Unreleased Movie\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Kerala Cafe]]'' ||   School girl  || [[Prithviraj Sukumaran|Prithviraj]], [[Maniyanpilla Raju]], [[Jayasurya]] || [[Shankar Ramakrishnan]] ||[[Malayalam]] ||Island Express (Second segment)\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[The Waiting Room (2010 film)|The Waiting Room]]'' ||  Girl killed   || [[Indrajith Sukumaran]], [[Sandeep Kulkarni]], [[Sona Nair]] || [[Maneej Premnath]] ||[[Hindi]] ||\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Chattakkari (2012 film)|Chattakaari]]'' ||  Usha  || [[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]], [[Shamna Kasim]], [[Sukumari]] ||Santosh Sethumadhavan  ||[[Malayalam]] ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Akam (film)|Akam]]'' || Tara    || [[Fahad Fazil]], [[Anumol]], [[Prakash Bare]] || Shalini Usha Nair ||[[Malayalam]] ||The film is a contemporary retelling of Malayattoor Ramakrishnan's classic psycho-thriller novel Yakshi (1967)\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Thanga Meenkal]]'' ||  Vadivu  || [[Ram (director)|Ram]], [[Padmapriya]], [[Rohini (actress)|Rohini]] ||[[Ram (director)|Ram]] ||[[Tamil language|Tamil]] ||Nominated \u2013 [[3rd South Indian International Movie Awards|3rd South Indian International Movie Awards for Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]<ref>http://entertainment.chennaipatrika.com/post/2014/07/17/SIIMA-Awards-Tamil-2014-Nominations-List.aspx</ref>\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Chirakinte Maravil'' ||  Susan  ||  || || [[Malayalam]]<br> Short film||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Sakhavu (2017 film)|Sakhavu]]'' ||  Maya || [[Nivin Pauly]], [[Aishwarya Rajesh]], [[Aparna Gopinath]]  ||Sidhartha Siva   || [[Malayalam]]||\n|-\n| 2018|| ''[[Eeda]]'' ||Leela ||[[Shane Nigam]], [[Nimisha Sajayan]]||[[B. Ajithkumar]]||[[Malayalam]]||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Serials==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!Year!! Title !! Language !!  Role !! Channel !! Notes\n|-\n|2017 \u2013 2020||''[[Sthreepadham]]'' || rowspan=9|[[Malayalam]] || Balasudha|| [[Mazhavil Manorama]] ||\n|-\n|2013||''[[Parasparam (TV series)|Parasparam]]'' ||rowspan=2|Shalini||rowspan=2|[[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]|| Guest appearance\n|-\